              "prompt": "Drill the core `_at`-variant refactor from a blank editor. Build a class `Bag` whose storage holds, for each key, a tuple `(value, set_at)` — the timestamp lives in the cell from day one.\n\nMethods:\n  - `set(key, value)` — untimed write; store at time `0`, i.e. `(value, 0)`.\n  - `get(key)` — return the value, or `None` if the key is absent.\n  - `set_at(key, value, timestamp)` — same storage shape, store `(value, timestamp)`.\n  - `get_at(key)` — return the value (same return shape as `get`), or `None` if absent.\n\nExample: `b = Bag(); b.set_at(\"a\", \"1\", 42)` → `b.get_at(\"a\")` returns `\"1\"` and the internal cell is `(\"1\", 42)`. `b.set(\"a\", \"x\")` makes the cell `(\"x\", 0)`.",
              "solution": "class Bag:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self._db = {}  # key -> (value, set_at)\n\n    def set(self, key, value):\n        # untimed write == write at time 0\n        self._db[key] = (value, 0)\n\n    def get(self, key):\n        cell = self._db.get(key)\n        return None if cell is None else cell[0]\n\n    def set_at(self, key, value, timestamp):\n        self._db[key] = (value, timestamp)\n\n    def get_at(self, key):\n        # same return shape; the timestamp is carried but get returns value\n        cell = self._db.get(key)\n        return None if cell is None else cell[0]\n",
