          "mode": "sync",
          "prompt": "Define three classes:\n\n1. `Animal(name)` — `speak()` returns `\"{name} makes a sound\"`\n2. `Dog(Animal)` — adds a `breed` attribute; `speak()` returns `\"{name} barks\"`\n3. `GuideDog(Dog)` — adds an `owner` attribute; `speak()` calls `super().speak()` and appends `\" (guide dog for {owner})\"`\n\nAll `__init__` methods must chain with `super().__init__(...)`.",
          "solution": "class Animal:\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n\n    def speak(self):\n        return f\"{self.name} makes a sound\"\n\n\nclass Dog(Animal):\n    def __init__(self, name, breed):\n        # super().__init__ chains to Animal's __init__ so self.name is set\n        super().__init__(name)\n        self.breed = breed\n\n    def speak(self):\n        # override the parent method entirely\n        return f\"{self.name} barks\"\n\n\nclass GuideDog(Dog):\n    def __init__(self, name, breed, owner):\n        super().__init__(name, breed)  # chains to Dog.__init__\n        self.owner = owner\n\n    def speak(self):\n        base = super().speak()         # reuse Dog.speak, then extend\n        return f\"{base} (guide dog for {self.owner})\"\n",
