          "type": "exercise",
          "kind": "recall",
          "mode": "sync",
          "prompt": "Write a `Coordinate` class holding a `lat` and `lon`.\n\n- `__repr__` is the developer-facing form: `Coordinate(40.7, -74.0)` — use `!r` so the numbers render via `repr()`.\n- `__str__` is the friendlier user-facing form: `40.7N, -74.0E`.\n\nExample: for `c = Coordinate(40.7, -74.0)`, `repr(c)` is `'Coordinate(40.7, -74.0)'`, while `str(c)` and `print(c)` both produce `'40.7N, -74.0E'` (because `print()` calls `__str__`, and the two forms intentionally differ).",
          "solution": "class Coordinate:\n    def __init__(self, lat, lon):\n        self.lat, self.lon = lat, lon\n\n    def __repr__(self):\n        # developer-facing; !r applies repr() to each value\n        return f\"Coordinate({self.lat!r}, {self.lon!r})\"\n\n    def __str__(self):\n        # user-facing; intentionally different from __repr__\n        return f\"{self.lat}N, {self.lon}E\"\n",
          "tests": "import unittest\nfrom solution import Coordinate\n\nclass ExerciseTests(unittest.TestCase):\n    def test_repr(self):\n        self.assertEqual(repr(Coordinate(40.7, -74.0)), \"Coordinate(40.7, -74.0)\")\n\n    def test_str(self):\n        self.assertEqual(str(Coordinate(40.7, -74.0)), \"40.7N, -74.0E\")\n\n    def test_repr_and_str_differ(self):\n        c = Coordinate(1, 2)\n        self.assertNotEqual(repr(c), str(c))\n\n    def test_print_uses_str(self):\n        import io, contextlib\n        buf = io.StringIO()\n        with contextlib.redirect_stdout(buf):\n            print(Coordinate(40.7, -74.0))\n        self.assertEqual(buf.getvalue().strip(), \"40.7N, -74.0E\")\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    unittest.main()\n"
