          "prompt": "CAPSTONE: Implement `decode_string(s)` (LC 394) entirely from memory and under time pressure.\n\nThis is the full production version:\n- Handle multi-digit counts (`10[a]`).\n- Handle deeply nested brackets (`2[2[a]]` -> `aaaa`).\n- Handle string prefixes before brackets (`2[ab3[c]]` -> `abcccabccc`).\n- Return the empty string for empty input.\n\nYou may NOT look back at previous lessons. Write the two-stack solution from scratch.",
          "solution": "def decode_string(s):\n    \"\"\"Capstone: decode nested encoded string from memory.\n\n    Two stacks track (1) the pending repeat counts and (2) the strings\n    accumulated before each '['.  On ']' we pop both, repeat, and stitch.\n    \"\"\"\n    count_stack = []\n    str_stack = []\n    current = \"\"\n    k = 0\n\n    for ch in s:\n        if ch.isdigit():\n            k = k * 10 + int(ch)\n        elif ch == '[':\n            count_stack.append(k)\n            str_stack.append(current)\n            current = \"\"\n            k = 0\n        elif ch == ']':\n            times = count_stack.pop()\n            prev = str_stack.pop()\n            current = prev + current * times\n        else:\n            current += ch\n\n    return current\n",
