          "prompt": "**Exercise 11 — Find Peak Element (LC 162)**\n\nWrite `find_peak_element(nums)`. A peak is any index `i` where `nums[i] > nums[i-1]` and `nums[i] > nums[i+1]`. Treat out-of-bounds neighbors as negative infinity. Return the index of ANY valid peak.\n\nRequirements:\n- O(log n)\n- Use `while lo < hi` — loop exits with `lo == hi == peak index`\n- At each `mid`: if `nums[mid] < nums[mid+1]`, a peak is to the right so `lo = mid + 1`; otherwise a peak is at `mid` or to its left so `hi = mid`\n- Return `lo`",
          "solution": "def find_peak_element(nums):\n    \"\"\"LC 162 - find peak element (any element greater than its neighbors).\n\n    Works even though the array is not fully sorted, because at any mid:\n    - if nums[mid] < nums[mid+1], a peak must exist in the right half\n    - otherwise, a peak must exist in the left half (including mid)\n    This gives O(log n) despite no global sort.\n    Edge: treat out-of-bounds indices as -infinity.\n    \"\"\"\n    lo, hi = 0, len(nums) - 1\n    while lo < hi:\n        mid = (lo + hi) // 2\n        if nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1]:\n            lo = mid + 1   # slope going up to the right; peak is right\n        else:\n            hi = mid        # slope going down to the right; peak is here or left\n    return lo\n",
