          "solution": "def has_cycle_directed(n, edges):\n    \"\"\"Detect cycle in a directed graph using DFS color-marking.\n\n    Colors: 0 = unvisited, 1 = in current DFS path (gray), 2 = done (black).\n    A back-edge to a gray node means a cycle exists.\n\n    Args:\n        n: number of nodes labeled 0..n-1\n        edges: list of [u, v] directed edges (u -> v)\n\n    Returns:\n        True if a cycle exists, False otherwise\n    \"\"\"\n    from collections import defaultdict\n    graph = defaultdict(list)\n    for u, v in edges:\n        graph[u].append(v)\n\n    color = [0] * n  # 0=white, 1=gray, 2=black\n\n    def dfs(node):\n        color[node] = 1  # mark as in-progress\n        for neighbor in graph[node]:\n            if color[neighbor] == 1:\n                return True   # back edge -> cycle\n            if color[neighbor] == 0:\n                if dfs(neighbor):\n                    return True\n        color[node] = 2  # done\n        return False\n\n    for node in range(n):\n        if color[node] == 0:\n            if dfs(node):\n                return True\n    return False\n",
