          "solution": "def can_finish(num_courses, prerequisites):\n    \"\"\"Determine if all courses can be finished without circular dependencies (LC 207).\n\n    Models prerequisites as a directed graph; a valid schedule exists iff the\n    graph is a DAG (no cycles). Uses DFS color marking.\n\n    Args:\n        num_courses: integer, courses labeled 0..num_courses-1\n        prerequisites: list of [a, b] meaning course a requires course b first\n\n    Returns:\n        True if all courses can be finished, False if a cycle makes it impossible\n    \"\"\"\n    from collections import defaultdict\n    graph = defaultdict(list)\n    for a, b in prerequisites:\n        graph[b].append(a)  # b must come before a\n\n    # 0=unvisited, 1=in-stack (gray), 2=done (black)\n    color = [0] * num_courses\n\n    def dfs(node):\n        color[node] = 1\n        for nxt in graph[node]:\n            if color[nxt] == 1:\n                return False  # cycle\n            if color[nxt] == 0:\n                if not dfs(nxt):\n                    return False\n        color[node] = 2\n        return True\n\n    for course in range(num_courses):\n        if color[course] == 0:\n            if not dfs(course):\n                return False\n    return True\n",
