          "prompt": "**Exercise 14 — Cumulative Capstone: Count Components (LC 323)**\n\nWrite `count_components_edges(n, edges)` — the complete end-to-end solution for counting connected components in an undirected graph with `n` nodes and an edge list. This exercise ties together every skill from the module: adjacency-list construction, DFS with a visited set, and component counting.\n\nRequirements:\n- Build `defaultdict(list)` adjacency list from `edges`.\n- Use iterative or recursive DFS — your choice.\n- Loop over `range(n)` to catch isolated nodes.\n- Return integer component count.\n\nThis is LC 323 (Number of Connected Components in an Undirected Graph) — a top-10 graph interview question.\n\n```python\nfrom collections import defaultdict\n\ndef count_components_edges(n, edges):\n    # your code here\n    pass\n```",
          "solution": "from collections import defaultdict\n\n\ndef count_components_edges(n, edges):\n    \"\"\"Count connected components given n nodes and an edge list (capstone).\n\n    This is the cumulative capstone: combines adjacency-list construction,\n    DFS traversal, and component counting in one clean function.\n    Analogous to LC 323 (Number of Connected Components in an Undirected Graph).\n\n    Args:\n        n: number of nodes labeled 0..n-1\n        edges: list of [u, v] undirected edges\n\n    Returns:\n        integer count of connected components\n    \"\"\"\n    graph = defaultdict(list)\n    for u, v in edges:\n        graph[u].append(v)\n        graph[v].append(u)\n\n    visited = set()\n    components = 0\n\n    def dfs(node):\n        visited.add(node)\n        for neighbor in graph[node]:\n            if neighbor not in visited:\n                dfs(neighbor)\n\n    for node in range(n):\n        if node not in visited:\n            dfs(node)\n            components += 1\n\n    return components\n",
