          "type": "text",
          "value": "## Permutations (LC 46) — a different structure\n\nPermutations differ from subsets in two key ways:\n- **Every element is used exactly once** in each permutation.\n- **Order matters** — `[1,2]` and `[2,1]` are different.\n\nWe can't use a `start` index because we may need any unused element from any position. Instead we use a `used[]` boolean array:\n\n```\nfor i in range(len(nums)):\n    if used[i]: continue\n    used[i] = True        # CHOOSE: mark as in-use\n    current.append(nums[i])\n    backtrack(current)    # RECURSE (no start — any unused element is valid)\n    current.pop()         # UN-CHOOSE\n    used[i] = False\n```\n\nBase case: when `len(current) == len(nums)`, record and return."
