          "solution": "def subsets_with_dup(nums):\n    \"\"\"\n    LC 90 - Subsets II.\n    Input may contain duplicates. Return all unique subsets.\n    Key insight: sort first, then skip duplicate siblings at the same depth level.\n    \"\"\"\n    nums.sort()\n    result = []\n\n    def backtrack(start, current):\n        result.append(list(current))\n\n        for i in range(start, len(nums)):\n            # Skip duplicate elements at the same recursive level\n            # (not the same as skipping the first occurrence)\n            if i > start and nums[i] == nums[i - 1]:\n                continue\n            # CHOOSE\n            current.append(nums[i])\n            # RECURSE\n            backtrack(i + 1, current)\n            # UN-CHOOSE\n            current.pop()\n\n    backtrack(0, [])\n    return result\n",
