          "solution": "def combination_sum2(candidates, target):\n    \"\"\"\n    LC 40 - Combination Sum II.\n    Each candidate may only be used ONCE. Input may contain duplicates.\n    Must return unique combinations.\n\n    Differences from LC39:\n    1. Sort so duplicates are adjacent.\n    2. Recurse with i+1 (not i) to prevent reuse.\n    3. Skip duplicate siblings at the same depth level (i > start and nums[i] == nums[i-1]).\n    \"\"\"\n    candidates.sort()\n    result = []\n\n    def backtrack(start, current, remaining):\n        if remaining == 0:\n            result.append(list(current))\n            return\n\n        for i in range(start, len(candidates)):\n            # Skip duplicate at same level\n            if i > start and candidates[i] == candidates[i - 1]:\n                continue\n            c = candidates[i]\n            if c > remaining:\n                break  # Pruning: sorted, so rest are also too large\n\n            # CHOOSE\n            current.append(c)\n            # RECURSE: i+1 because each element used at most once\n            backtrack(i + 1, current, remaining - c)\n            # UN-CHOOSE\n            current.pop()\n\n    backtrack(0, [], target)\n    return result\n",
