          "prompt": "**LC 215 variant — Kth Largest via MAX-heap**\n\nImplement `find_kth_largest_negate(nums, k)` using the full-heap approach:\n\n1. Negate every element: `heap = [-x for x in nums]`.\n2. `heapq.heapify(heap)` — O(n), faster than n pushes.\n3. Pop `k` times; each pop returns the current maximum (after un-negating). The k-th pop is the answer.\n\nThis is O(n + k log n) — it processes the full heap rather than a size-k window. Both approaches are correct; this one emphasizes the negation idiom directly.\n\nHandles: `k=1`, `k=len(nums)`, negatives, duplicates, single element.",
          "solution": "import heapq\n\n\ndef find_kth_largest_negate(nums, k):\n    # Negate every element so Python's min-heap acts as a max-heap\n    heap = [-x for x in nums]\n    heapq.heapify(heap)   # O(n) — faster than n individual pushes\n    val = 0\n    for _ in range(k):\n        val = -heapq.heappop(heap)   # undo negation on the way out\n    return val\n",
