          "mode": "sync",
          "prompt": "LC57 Insert Interval.\n\nGiven a sorted, non-overlapping list of intervals and one `new_interval = [start, end]`, insert `new_interval` and merge any overlapping intervals. Return the resulting sorted list.\n\n**Three-phase approach:**\n1. While `intervals[i][1] < new_interval[0]`: append interval as-is (ends before new one starts).\n2. While `intervals[i][0] <= new_interval[1]`: merge into `new_interval` (expand bounds with min/max). Then append `new_interval`.\n3. Append all remaining intervals.\n\nYou may mutate `new_interval` directly. The function is `insert(intervals, new_interval)`.",
          "solution": "def insert(intervals, new_interval):\n    \"\"\"\n    LC57 Insert Interval — insert newInterval into a sorted, non-overlapping list.\n\n    Three phases in a single pass:\n    1. Collect all intervals that END before new_interval starts (no overlap, add as-is).\n    2. Merge all intervals that OVERLAP with new_interval (extend new_interval's bounds).\n    3. Collect all remaining intervals (they start after the merged result ends).\n\n    Overlap check: interval[0] <= new_interval[1] and new_interval[0] <= interval[1]\n    (equivalently: NOT (interval[1] < new_interval[0] or interval[0] > new_interval[1]))\n\n    Time O(n), Space O(n) for output.\n    \"\"\"\n    result = []\n    i = 0\n    n = len(intervals)\n\n    # Phase 1: intervals that end before new_interval starts.\n    while i < n and intervals[i][1] < new_interval[0]:\n        result.append(intervals[i])\n        i += 1\n\n    # Phase 2: merge overlapping intervals into new_interval.\n    while i < n and intervals[i][0] <= new_interval[1]:\n        new_interval[0] = min(new_interval[0], intervals[i][0])\n        new_interval[1] = max(new_interval[1], intervals[i][1])\n        i += 1\n    result.append(new_interval)\n\n    # Phase 3: intervals that start after the merged interval ends.\n    while i < n:\n        result.append(intervals[i])\n        i += 1\n\n    return result\n",
          "tests": "import unittest\nfrom solution import insert\n\n\nclass TestInsert(unittest.TestCase):\n    def test_basic_overlap(self):\n        result = insert([[1, 3], [6, 9]], [2, 5])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 5], [6, 9]])\n\n    def test_multiple_merges(self):\n        result = insert([[1, 2], [3, 5], [6, 7], [8, 10], [12, 16]], [4, 8])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 2], [3, 10], [12, 16]])\n\n    def test_insert_at_start(self):\n        result = insert([[3, 5], [7, 9]], [1, 2])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 2], [3, 5], [7, 9]])\n\n    def test_insert_at_end(self):\n        result = insert([[1, 3], [5, 7]], [8, 10])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 3], [5, 7], [8, 10]])\n\n    def test_empty_intervals(self):\n        result = insert([], [2, 5])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[2, 5]])\n\n    def test_touching_start(self):\n        # new_interval ends exactly where next starts\n        result = insert([[3, 5]], [1, 3])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 5]])\n\n    def test_touching_end(self):\n        # new_interval starts exactly where previous ends\n        result = insert([[1, 3]], [3, 5])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 5]])\n\n    def test_contained(self):\n        # new_interval fully inside an existing interval\n        result = insert([[1, 10]], [3, 5])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 10]])\n\n    def test_no_overlap(self):\n        result = insert([[1, 2], [7, 8]], [4, 5])\n        self.assertEqual(result, [[1, 2], [4, 5], [7, 8]])\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    unittest.main()\n"
